\f0\fs24 \cf0 Today is the birthday of 
\f1\b\fs28 \cf2 \cb3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Michael Faraday
\f0\b0  \cf4 (\cf2 1791-1867), English {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientist"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 scientist}} who contributed to the study of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnetism"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 electromagnetism}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrochemistry"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 electrochemistry}}. His main discoveries include the principles underlying {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnetic_induction"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 electromagnetic induction}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diamagnetism"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 diamagnetism}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrolysis"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 electrolysis}}.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Although Faraday received little formal education, he was one of the most influential scientists in history. It was by his research on the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnetic_field"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 magnetic field}} around a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electrical_conductor"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 conductor}} carrying a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Direct_current"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 direct current}} that Faraday established the basis for the concept of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electromagnetic_field"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 electromagnetic field}} in physics. Faraday also established that {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetism"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 magnetism}} could affect {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ray_(optics)"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 rays of light}} and that there was an underlying relationship between the two phenomena. He similarly discovered the principles of electromagnetic induction and diamagnetism, and the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faraday%27s_laws_of_electrolysis"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 laws of electrolysis}}. His {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invention"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 inventions}} of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electric_motor"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 electromagnetic rotary devices}} formed the foundation of electric motor technology, and it was largely due to his efforts that {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electricity"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 electricity}} became practical for use in technology.\cb1 \
\cb3 \
Faraday was an excellent experimentalist who conveyed his ideas in clear and simple language; his mathematical abilities, however, did not extend as far as {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trigonometry"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 trigonometry}} and were limited to the simplest algebra. {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Clerk_Maxwell"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 James Clerk Maxwell}} took the work of Faraday and others and summarized it in a set of equations which is accepted as the basis of all modern theories of electromagnetic phenomena. \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Albert_Einstein"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Albert Einstein}} kept a picture of Faraday on his study wall, alongside pictures of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Isaac Newton}} and James Clerk Maxwell. Physicist {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ernest_Rutherford"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 Ernest Rutherford}} stated, "When we consider the magnitude and extent of his discoveries and their influence on the progress of science and of industry, there is no honour too great to pay to the memory of Faraday, one of the greatest scientific discoverers of all time."
